Analysing and Visualising the Dataset of OFDb about Super8 Italian Films¶

In this notebook I would like to analyse a dataset that comes from the OFDb.de Website, a community supported website that also features several Super8/16mm versions of films. Most of the small gauge versions from Germany are actually Super8 Version as it is demonstrated by the Company which were the actual distributors such as Marketing, UFA Büscher Film and Piccolo Film. This dataset contains thus a list of exclusively italian film productions and few italian co-productions that were distributed by UFA-Buscher Film, Piccolo Film and Marketing Film in Germany in the seventies and early eighties. These companies specialised in the distribution of "reduction prints" (reduced versions of films to be watched at home) on Super8-mm film material and had a specific library of film genres. In my analysis I want to give a glimpse in form of a "distant reading" of the film library, the most represented genres, directors, country of origins and original language of the distributions, in order to understand what was popular among reduction prints buyers.

In [ ]:

The Dataset has been enriched with additional data through the software Open Refine. To the original Title of the films I added and reconciled the original title (the Ufa title was usually different than the original copy because reduction prints were often edited and shortened versions). From the original title I could add other fields as columns: director, original language, genre (limited to only 1 item), IMDb ID, year of production and country of origin.

Looking at other people work on film lists I also want to show only the most frequent genres and group those that are coming less often into a single group in order to visualize it better in a chart. I took part of the code from github page of CamPaiva.

In [10]:
#counting the frequency of genres per film 

genre_list = pd.DataFrame(italofilm_df.genre.value_counts())
genre_list["Frequency"] = italofilm_df.genre.value_counts(normalize=True)
genre_list = genre_list.reset_index()
genre_list = genre_list.rename(columns = {"index": "genre", "count": "Number of Films"})
genre_list.loc[genre_list.Frequency < 0.03, 'genre'] = 'Others'
genre_list = (genre_list
                .groupby('genre').sum()
                .sort_values('Number of Films', ascending=False)
                .reset_index())
print(genre_list)

A pie chart might represent the percentages within the whole dataset better. Let's see. I added a legend on the bottom right corner. We might see that the most represented genres are comedy, action and horror film. Even science fiction has a higher percentage than drama. This shows how this dataset of films might differ from the most popular films in theaters. These films were only distributed for the home entertainment.

# Combine values from the specified columns into a single column
country_columns = ['Co_production_country', 'Co_production_country_2', 'Co_production_country_3']
combined_countries = italofilm_df[country_columns].stack().reset_index(drop=True)

# Replace "West Germany" with "Germany"
combined_countries = combined_countries.replace('West Germany', 'Germany')


# Exclude the specific country (e.g., Italy)
excluded_country = 'Italy'
combined_countries = combined_countries[combined_countries != excluded_country]

# Count the occurrences of each country
country_counts = combined_countries.value_counts()

# Plot a pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 9))
plt.pie(country_counts, labels=country_counts.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', pctdistance=0.7, startangle=160)
plt.title('Distribution of Co-productions Countries for Italian Films')
plt.show()

plt.savefig("Italofilm_Co_production_Pie.jpg")

# Count the occurrences of each country in the 'Co_production_country' column
co_production_counts = italofilm_df['Co_production_country'].value_counts()

# Calculate the percentage distribution
co_production_percentages = (co_production_counts / len(italofilm_df)) * 100

# Create a "Total" category by subtracting the sum of individual countries from 100%
co_production_percentages['Total'] = 100 - co_production_percentages.sum()

# Plot a bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
co_production_percentages.plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue')
plt.title('Percentage Distribution of Co-productions in Italian Films')
plt.xlabel('Co-production Country')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Total Entries')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.show()
In [16]:
# Count the occurrences of each value in the 'Co_production_country' column
co_production_counts = italofilm_df['Co_production_country'].value_counts()

# Calculate the percentage distribution
co_production_percentages = (co_production_counts / len(italofilm_df)) * 100

# Create a "national productions" category by subtracting the sum of individual countries from 100%
co_production_percentages['national productions'] = 100 - co_production_percentages.sum()

# Sum all individual country percentages for the "co-productions" category
co_productions_percentage = co_production_percentages.drop('national productions').sum()

# Create a DataFrame for the pie chart
pie_data = pd.Series({'national productions': co_production_percentages['national productions'],
                     'co-productions': co_productions_percentage})

# Plot a pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
pie_data.plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140)
plt.title('Distribution of National Productions and Co-productions in Italian Films')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.show()
